 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eandori>Eandori</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 578<br> <font color=#333333>(2/11/03 12:37:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=394.topic&index=249>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_cry.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: /shrug</span><hr size=1> I was one of the more vocal mages during the Kunark expansion.  In fact, on the list of questions we sent to Verant, 6 out of the ~80 questions were from me.  I created my mage in Dec 1999 and I have played him non-stop ever since then.  Hoping that justifies my experience on this topic, I'll continue to add my opinion.<br>
<br>
My original statement way back in Kunark, and I stand by it today, is that the Damage related caster classes should be kings of burst DPS, and the Damage related melee classes should be kings of sustained DPS.  That way, each has an advantage, and a reason for being.  You would want a caster for those super high DPS required periods.  You would want a melee for the nonstop DPS periods.  You could make due with either one.  The balanced group would have a little of both.<br>
<br>
This seemed like a good analogy to me, because it was obviously the way the game was supposed to work.  Both players did damage, but one had a limit, a mana pool.  While the other could nearly go indefinately.  <br>
<br>
The problem of Kunark, as I perceived it, was that Melee were surpassing my burst DPS.  I had no qualms about them outdoing my sustained DPS, but to beat my burst was just flat out wrong.  Back then, it took around 13 min to med back to full, and I could spend that mana in 40 seconds.  These days, with Flowing Thought, KEI, Other buffs, Mental Clarity, Pet Canni, etc.  We mages can recover mana MUCH faster.  So much faster, that now our sustained DPS is extremely high.<br>
<br>
In my opinion, this is where the unbalance is.  A melee like a monk should NOT match my DPS when I'm nuking with pet.  They should not even be close.  But then I should be recovering mana and they should catch up and surpass my total damage.  As Everquest currently sits, my burst DPS is far and above any melee.  At the same time, my sustained DPS is above theirs.  THAT is where I will agree with you that mages are extremely powerfull.<br>
<br>
Having said that, we need to make sure we are comparing the classes equally.  But that's just the problem, you can't compare them equally.  A mage does indeed have a severe lack of other casters skills, which is why I believe we are damage kings.  A monk has abilities that a warrior and rogue cannot touch.  I'll give you a general comment to chew on here.<br>
<br>
=============================================<br>
A class cannot be balanced by just looking at a few zones in PoP.  A class MUST be balanced by looking at that class's entire life in all zones, at all levels, and in all situations.<br>
=============================================<br>
<br>
As far as I remember, before any expansions, Monks were not supposed to be a soloing class.  The fact you guys can solo was a testament to how powerfull you became.  You tanked as well as warriors, you had superior HP regen with items/skills.  You had very low risk with Feign death, and you had nearly the top DPS.  That was way too much.  I would agree with you that Monks got hit too hard with the nerf stick, but the did need some changing.  Now it would be best to find a roll and place monks in it.  <br>
<br>
Don't lead off by nerfing other classes.  Many of us are balanced to the game content as it sits.  If you nerf other classes then the game itself will be unbalanced.  Instead, it would be better to re-affirm the &quot;proper&quot; role for a monk, and work on filling that role.  Mage pets are where they should be.  Your class needs to be altered to fit in the picture better.  Wizards should not complain about mage nukes, they have their own advantages.  They just need to work on making their nuke choices more available. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">Master Eandori Raintree<br>
60/61 Arch Mage<br>
 <br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=36994">My Magelo</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.geocities.com/enigmasolro">The Lords of Prophecy</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
The Blinding, Rooting, Epic pet casting Gimp Mage of Sol Ro!<br>
</div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=benzai>Benzai</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#333333>(2/12/03 11:24:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=394.topic&index=250>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_cry.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: /shrug</span><hr size=1> I totally agree with you Eandori.  Having played on both sides of the fence, I think I judge both classes fairly well, and I think you assess class balance, and how it should be, very well.  Burst damage vs. sustained, is very important.<br>
<br>
Monks actually could solo from 1 to 50, before Kunark, before Fungi's, before T-staffs, though.  It wasn't efficient, and most chose not to go that route, but some did and it was possible.  The abilities of the monk ensured that soloing was always an option.  Feign was an instant escape and reset (a virtual &quot;do over&quot;, if you will) if the fight went poorly, having a 25% heal every 6 minutes (mend) and maxing bind wounds skill (84 hit points per bind ain't too shabby), instill doubt at level 17, decent naked damage, etc.  Just because monks can't solo like a necro doesn't mean they haven't had the ability.<br>
<br>
True at higher levels it gets more difficult.  But then the ol' Fungi and other neat toys were introduced in the game and this made it even easier to solo.  The T-staff, with it's unresistable 0-12 second stun, and being a 2 hander, with far fewer repostes, made soloing even easier.  Now we have toys that summon bandages, increase regen, etc. and defensive disciplines like Stonestance, which refresh ~ every 3 minutes, and it's not hard to believe why monks weren't decent soloers.  Stating that monks never were meant to be soloers, or that the fact that they could solo, shouldn't mean that monks were overpowered or broken.  The fact is, the monk has always possessed a good staple of tools at his disposal to kill a mob before being killed.<br>
<br>
One doesn't guage class balance in regards to whether they can solo or not, however.  If that were the case, necromancers would have continued to get nerfed into the stone age and magicians would have followed.  The only gripes I had about soloing my mage was that it took too damn long to regen mana, thus it was innefficient and boring.  This was before KEI entered the game, however.  Personally, I don't buy the &quot;some classes were designed to be solo classes&quot; either.  Enchanters were really tooled to be one of the most attractive classes a group could hunt for, with incredible utility and usefullness but at the cost of offensive prowess, but charm-soloing, while risky, is viable and the rewards can be excessive.  In fact, the beastlord was released long after many of these &quot;which class is a solo class?&quot; issues were discussed and long after VI (remember them, before Sony?) stated they don't exactly endorse soloing in a group-based game that revolves around being social.  They seem to contradict themselves a lot, it seems.<br>
<br>
Anyway, there seems to be a lot to discuss.  I don't think a pet should out perform the functions of the players that fulfill the roles, otherwise their role in the game is removed and you may as well just delete the class from the game.  I personally wouldn't mind having a pet tank for me in an xp group if there was no plate class around, but Sony refuses to let a player get in melee range and allow the pet's taunt ability to work, so we all suffer as a result.  <br>
<br>
It just means less options for us, when we're all LFG, and so people get stuck in the holy trinity mind-set for the perfect group.  As it is, if I, as a monk, am in a group with 2 mages, a chanter, a cleric and a ranger, for example, hunting in PoP, there is nothing I can do other than pull mobs and throw shurikens for max 20 damage, since I certainly cannot tank (maybe I can, against tier 1 yard trash, if the're properly slowed and I'm sufficiently buffed, but it's still not near as efficient as just letting a pet or charmed mob do the job).  Unfortunately, these limitations exist, for better or for worse (I think for worse) keeps people from developing creative tactics and options in grouping, and lessens the class envy rants that develop because these options don't exist and we aren't allowed to be flexible. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>Benzai Hongkongfooey<br>
Guardian Drunk of Saryrn<br>
Grandmaster of Forever<br>
